`template/scripts/` is a set of standalone offline CI gate scripts plus a one-time bootstrap script, invoked by `ctx-verify`/CI to fail the build on lint/dependency/style violations without needing network access or a full cargo build.

All five check scripts (`cycle_check.sh`, `machete_check.sh`, `no_allow_check.sh`, `rationale_check.py`, `workspace_lints_check.sh`) share a `FAIL: <path>[:<line>]: <message>` stdout convention and a nonzero-exit-on-failure contract that downstream tooling (ctx-verify) parses; changing that output shape in one script without checking the others breaks parsing uniformly. Three of them (`no_allow_check.sh`, `rationale_check.py`, `workspace_lints_check.sh`) deliberately enumerate files via `git ls-files -z --cached --others --exclude-standard` rather than a filesystem walk, specifically to avoid racing a concurrent `cargo`/rust-analyzer writer into `target/`; any new check added to this directory should follow the same pattern rather than reintroducing `find`/`rglob`.

`cycle_check.sh` is a placeholder — it only confirms `cargo modules dependencies` runs, real cycle detection is deferred to a future dylint rule. `machete_check.sh` wraps `cargo-machete`'s ambiguous exit code with output-parsing plus a fallback generic failure so errors are never silently swallowed. `no_allow_check.sh` and `rationale_check.py` both police in-source code shape (banning `#[allow]`, requiring `// rationale:` comments on oversized functions/files) and are both explicitly MVP stand-ins for dylint rules. `workspace_lints_check.sh` checks manifest shape only (`[lints]\nworkspace = true` presence), not the meaningful content of `[workspace.lints]`.

`install-tools.sh` is unrelated to the check scripts: it's a one-time bootstrap that builds and copies `ctx-*` binaries and summarizer prompts from a sibling tooling repo into the local project so the other scripts and hooks have their binaries available.